"{\n  \"text\": \"Every culture before refrigeration fermented their foods. Most food preservation nowadays is through a sterilization of all bacteria. Before this was a common method, people would use healthy bacteria, anaerobic or bacteria without oxygen, or that thrives without oxygen to kill the bad bacteria that make us sick, the aerobic bacteria, the bacteria that uses oxygen to metabolize things, because we have an anaerobic bacterial system digesting things. So consequently, all this food-borne or all this aerobic bacteria that we live around, because we live in an oxygen-rich world, is contaminating our food. So we need to eat fresh foods, and then we can also preserve foods by creating anaerobic environment that will cultivate this anaerobic or without oxygen bacteria. Once the anaerobic bacteria is going after the food, it creates a barrier to the aerobic bacteria that's going to make it rot, wilt, turn black, mold, and all the things that we don't want with our food make it unedible. And so this is what fermentation is. It's very, very old. Every culture before refrigeration fermented their foods. This was a part of life. You did not live without your vegetables, and your vegetables are only available for about three weeks to a month. So you ferment to keep those vegetables good all season, and that's the way we've lived.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Every culture before refrigeration fermented their foods.\",\n      \"start\": 0.16,\n      \"end\": 5.04,\n      \"duration\": 4.88,\n      \"confidence\": 0.995,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" E\",\n          \"start\": 0.16,\n          \"end\": 0.24,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.972\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ver\",\n          \"start\": 0.24,\n          \"end\": 0.4,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n    